      <hedline>
        <hl1>Mideast Turmoil Is Like No Other</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Robert W Lebovits letter contends Israeli nationalists and conservatives feel 'the most acute pain' over return to violence in Mideast</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Thomas L. Friedman (column, Oct. 13) writes of the Israeli right wing's ''I told you so'' attitude regarding Yasir Arafat and Palestinian violence. Mr. Friedman and others paint a picture of a smug and self-satisfied segment of the Israeli public that is reveling in vindication over Arab rejection of peace offerings.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Thomas L. Friedman (column, Oct. 13) writes of the Israeli right wing's ''I told you so'' attitude regarding Yasir Arafat and Palestinian violence. Mr. Friedman and others paint a picture of a smug and self-satisfied segment of the Israeli public that is reveling in vindication over Arab rejection of peace offerings.</p>
        <p>In fact, Israeli nationalists and conservatives feel the most acute pain over the return to violence. They and their families are in harm's greatest way. Mr. Arafat's refusal to be a partner in peace will affect these Israelis most of all.</p>
        <p>ROBERT W. LEBOVITS  Pittsburgh, Oct. 13, 2000</p>
      </block>
